            ==English==
            ===Etymology===
            {{root|en|ine-pro|*hâ‚‚ey-|*kÊ·-|*-teros}}
            From {{inh|en|enm|either}}, from {{inh|en|ang|Ç£Ä¡hwÃ¦Ã¾er}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|-}}, ultimately
            corresponding to {{m|en|ay||always, ever}} + {{m|en|whether}}. Akin to Old Saxon {{m|osx|eogihwethar}},
            {{m|osx|iahwethar}} (Low German {{m|nds|jeed}}); Old Dutch {{m|odt|*iogewether}}, {{m|odt|*iowether}},
            {{m|odt|*iother}} (Dutch {{m|nl|ieder}}); Old High German {{m|goh|eogihwedar}}, {{m|goh|iegihweder}},
            {{m|goh|ieweder}} (German {{m|de|jeder}}).
            ===Pronunciation===
            * {{enPR|Ä«â€²''th''É™(r)|Ä“â€²''th''É™(r)}} {{IPA|en|/ËˆaÉª.Ã°É™(É¹)/|/ËˆiË.Ã°É™(É¹)/}}
            ** {{audio|en|en-uk-either.ogg|Audio (UK)}}, {{audio|en|en-us-either.ogg|Audio (US)}}
            * {{rhymes|en|aÉªÃ°É™(É¹)|iËÃ°É™(É¹)|s=2}}
            * {{q|obsolete (in use until the 20th c.)}} {{enPR|Äâ€²''th''É™(r)}} {{IPA|en|/ËˆeÉª.Ã°É™(É¹)/}}
            * In the UK, {{IPAchar|/aÉª/}} is used more in Southern England, and {{IPAchar|/iË/}} is more usual in
            Northern England. In North America, {{IPAchar|/iË/}} is the most common, but {{IPAchar|/aÉª/}} is predominant
            in some regions. Note that even if one pronunciation is more common in a region, the pronunciation used
            varies by individual speaker and sometimes by situation. {{IPAchar|/eÉª/}} was once heard in Northern
            England, but has now largely fallen into disuse.<ref>"Pronunciation: Either". Reader's
            Digest. (1964). ''The Complete Atlas of the British Isles'', p. 123.</ref>
            ===Determiner===
            {{en-det}}
            # Any one (of two).
            #: {{ux|en|You can have it in '''either''' colour.}}
            # Each of two; both. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
            #: {{ux|en|There is a locomotive at '''either''' end of the train, one pulling and the other pushing.}}
            #* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=3|passage=His flowing hair <br> In curls on '''either''' cheek
            played.}}
            #* '''1936''', {{w|Djuna Barnes}}, ''{{w|Nightwood}}'', Faber & Faber 2007, page 31:
            #*: Her hands, long and beautiful, lay on '''either''' side of her face.
            # {{lb|en|now|rare}} Any one (of more than two).
            #* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|letter=51|text=They ''entreat'', they ''pray'', they ''beg'', they
            ''supplicate'' (will '''either''' of these do, Miss Clary?) that you will make no scruple to go to your
            uncle Antony's {{â€¦}}.}}
            ====Usage notes====
            * When there are more than two alternatives, in the sense of â€œone of manyâ€, {{m|en|any}} is now generally
            used instead.
            ====Synonyms====
            * {{sense|each of two}} {{l|en|both}}, {{l|en|each}}
