{{also|Jump}}
            ==English==
            ===Pronunciation===
            * {{a|UK|US}} {{enPR|jÅ­mp}}, {{IPA|en|/dÊ’ÊŒmp/|[dÍ¡Ê’ÊŒmp]}}
            * {{audio|en|en-us-jump.ogg|Audio (US)}}
            * {{rhymes|en|ÊŒmp|s=1}}
            ===Etymology 1===
            [[File:NwFusionTapM.jpg|thumb|125px|A tap dancer jumping.]]
            From {{inh|en|enm|jumpen|t=to walk quickly, run, jump}}, probably of {{der|en|gml|-}} or {{der|en|gmq|-}}
            origin, ultimately from {{der|en|gem-pro|*gempanÄ…}}, {{m|gem-pro|*gembanÄ…|t=to hop, skip, jump}}, from
            {{der|en|ine-pro|*gÊ·Ê°emb-|t=to spring, hop, jump}}. The OED instead suggests an
            {{onomatopoeic|en|title=imitative}} origin.<ref>{{R:OED}}</ref> Related to {{l|en|jumble}}.
            {{rel-top|Cognates}}
            Cognate with {{cog|dum|gumpen||to jump}}, {{cog|nds|jumpen||to jump}}, {{cog|gmh|gumpen}},
            {{m|gmh|gampen||to jump, hop}} (dialectal {{cog|de|gampen}}, {{cog|gsw|gumpe}}, [[Walser]] dialect
            {{m|de|kumpu}}), {{cog|da|gumpe||to jolt}}, {{cog|sv|gumpa||to jump}}, {{cog|da|gimpe||to move up and
            down}}, {{cog|enm|jumpren}}, {{m|enm|jumbren||to mix, jumble}}. {{rel-bottom}}
            ====Verb====
            {{en-verb}}
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[propel]] oneself [[rapidly]] [[upward]], [[downward]] and/or in any horizontal
            direction such that [[momentum]] causes the [[body]] to become [[airborne]].
            #: {{ux|en|The boy '''jumped''' over a fence.}}
            #: {{ux|en|Kangaroos are known for their ability to '''jump''' high.}}
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Winter's Tale|IV|iv|passage=Not the worst of the three but '''jumps''' twelve foot and a
            half by the square.}}
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To cause oneself to [[leave]] an [[elevated]] location and fall [[downward]].
            #: {{ux|en|She is going to '''jump''' from the diving board.}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To pass by a spring or leap; to overleap.
            #: {{ux|en|to '''jump''' a stream}}
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To employ a [[parachute]] to leave an [[aircraft]] or elevated location.
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To react to a [[sudden]], often [[unexpected]], [[stimulus]] (such as a [[sharp]]
            [[prick]] or a loud sound) by [[jerk]]ing the body [[violently]].
            #: {{ux|en|The sudden sharp sound made me '''jump'''.}}
            # {{lb|en|intransitive|figuratively}} To [[increase]] sharply, to [[rise]], to [[shoot up]].
            #: {{ux|en|Share prices '''jumped''' by 10% after the company announced record profits.}}
            # {{lb|en|intransitive}} To employ a [[move]] in certain [[board games]] where one game piece is moved from
            one legal [[position]] to another [[pass]]ing over the position of another piece.
            #: {{ux|en|The player's knight '''jumped''' the opponent's bishop.}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To move to a position (in a [[queue]]/[[line]]) that is further forward.
            #: {{ux|en|I hate it when people '''jump''' the queue.}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[attack]] suddenly and violently.
            #: {{ux|en|The hoodlum '''jumped''' a woman in the alley.}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To engage in [[sexual intercourse]] with (a person).
            #* '''1983''', ''[[w:The Big Chill (film)|The Big Chill]]'':
            #*: Harold: How is Sarah? I don't want to '''jump''' her while she's [[on the rag]].
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cause]] to jump.
            #: {{ux|en|The rider '''jumped''' the horse over the fence.}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To move the distance between two opposing subjects.
            # {{lb|en|transitive}} To increase the [[height]] of a [[tower crane]] by inserting a section at the base of
            the tower and jacking up everything above it.
            # {{lb|en|cycling|intransitive}} To [[increase]] [[speed]] aggressively and without warning.
            # {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To expose to danger; to risk; to hazard.
            #* {{RQ:Shakespeare Coriolanus|III|i|passage=to '''jump''' a body with a dangerous physic}}
            # {{lb|en|transitive|smithwork}} To join by a [[buttweld]].
            # To [[thicken]] or [[enlarge]] by [[endwise]] [[blows]]; to [[upset]].
            # {{lb|en|quarrying}} To [[bore]] with a [[jumper]].
            # To [[jump-start]] a car or other vehicle with a dead [[battery]], as with [[jumper cable]]s.
            #* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=United States. Employees' Compensation Appeals Board|title=Decisions of
            the Employees' Compensation Appeals Board: Index digest|page=511
